Day 1: What is Django & How It Works 

Why do we even need Django?
Problem with only HTML/CSS/JS
If I ask:
Save user data 


Login system 


Store notes 


Admin panel 


Because:
Browser cannot talk directly to database
So we need:
Browser → Backend → Database

Django can:
Receive request from browser
Decide what logic to run
Talk to database
Send response back (HTML / JSON)





Django
Frontend
Backend framework
UI
Runs on server
Runs in browser
Uses Python
Uses HTML/CSS/JS




Django generates HTML, but it is still backend.

Django Architecture (VERY IMPORTANT)
Django follows MVT
Let’s rename it for understanding:
Model   → Data (Database)
View    → Brain (Logic)
Template→ Design (HTML)








Real-life analogy:
Amazon order
Part
Django
Real life
Data
Model
Warehouse
Logic
View
Manager
UI
Template
Delivery box


Django Project vs Django App (CONFUSION POINT)
Django Project
Whole website


Settings, configs


Django App
One feature/module


Example:
Instagram (Project)
│
├── accounts (App)
├── posts (App)
├── chat (App)

One project = many apps


Starting with django:
Create virtual environment, activate it : python3 -m venv virtualenvname / 
virtualenv name  
Activate : for windows : name\Scripts\activate 
For mac: source name/bin/activate
pip3 install django
Run this command and check if it is installed : django-admin --version
django-admin startproject project_name 
Use this to run the django file : python manage.py runserver

Folder structure you are seeing:
myproject/
│
├── manage.py
└── myproject/

Outer folder = project container
Inner folder = Django configuration

Django separates:
Management commands (outer)
Project configuration (inner)
So:
manage.py stays outside
Settings stay inside
manage.py
Purpose:
This file is used to run Django commands.
Examples:
python manage.py runserver
python manage.py startapp appname

Analogy:
Like npm for Django.

What is Admin Panel in Django?
Django Admin Panel is a ready-made dashboard to manage website data without writing extra code.
What can Admin Panel do?
From admin panel, you can:
Add data
Edit data
Delete data
Manage users
Control permissions


All via browser UI, not code.
Admin panel is NOT for normal users
It is ONLY for the website owner / developer

Understanding urls.py (VERY IMPORTANT FILE)
from django.contrib import admin
Meaning:
Django provides an admin panel
This line imports it
If removed → admin won’t work.

from django.urls import path
Meaning:
path() is used to define URLs
Without this, Django cannot map URLs
urlpatterns = []
Meaning:
A list of URL rules
Django checks this list top to bottom
Say:
“If URL is not here, Django doesn’t know it.”

path('admin/', admin.site.urls)
Meaning:
If URL starts with admin/
Send request to Django admin
User opens:
http://127.0.0.1:8000/admin/
Django:
Matches admin/


Sends request to admin.site.urls


Admin panel opens




Adding Our Own Page
STEP 1: Import HttpResponse
Add:
from django.http import HttpResponse
Explanation:
HTTP = how web works


Response = what server sends back


This class helps Django send text to browser


STEP 2: Create a View Function
Add:
def home(request):
    return HttpResponse("Hello Django")
Django automatically passes request
STEP 3: Connect URL to Function
Add:
path('', home)

Meaning:
'' → root URL


home → function to call


Final urls.py (complete):

from django.contrib import admin
from django.urls import path
from django.http import HttpResponse

def home(request):
    return HttpResponse("Hello Django")

urlpatterns = [
    path('admin/', admin.site.urls),
    path('', home),
]

Also try:
urls.py
from django.contrib import admin
from django.urls import path
from django.http import HttpResponse


def home(request):
   return HttpResponse("hello world")
def second_page(request):
   return HttpResponse("<h1>Second Page</h1>")
def third(request):
   return HttpResponse("third")
def second2(request):
   return HttpResponse("second 2")
urlpatterns = [
   path("admin/", admin.site.urls),
   path("",home),
   path("second/",second_page),
   path("third/",third),
   path("second/second_next",second2)
]




Why views.py Exists & What a Django App Is
“If our website has 50 pages…
will we write 50 functions inside urls.py?”
This is why Django separates responsibilities.
urls.py decides WHERE to go
views.py decides WHAT to do

What is a Django App? 
Simple definition :
A Django app is a module that handles ONE feature of a website.
Examples:
blog


notes


accounts


courses


One project → many apps.
Create Your First Django App
Run this command from the folder where manage.py exists:
python manage.py startapp main

Explain:
startapp → create feature


main → name of feature



Move logic OUT of urls.py
views.py -> 
from django.shortcuts import render
from django.http import HttpResponse


# Create your views here.
def home(request):
   return HttpResponse("hey")
def second_page(request):
   return HttpResponse("second page")


urls.py->
from django.contrib import admin
from django.urls import path
from main import views


urlpatterns = [
   path("admin/", admin.site.urls),
   path("",views.home),
   path("second/",views.second_page)
]
FINAL MENTAL MODEL 
Browser
 ↓
urls.py   → decides route
 ↓
views.py → runs logic
 ↓
HttpResponse
 ↓
Browser










When using apps, Django expects templates inside the app folder.
When we create an app using:
python manage.py startapp main
Django does NOT automatically use it.


In settings.py:
INSTALLED_APPS = [
    'django.contrib.admin',
    'django.contrib.auth',
    'django.contrib.contenttypes',
    'django.contrib.sessions',
    'django.contrib.messages',
    'django.contrib.staticfiles',


    'main',
]


We must register it.






Correct folder structure:
main/
├── views.py
├── templates/
│   └── home.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
   <title>Home</title>
</head>
<body>
   <h1>Welcome to Django</h1>
   <p>This page is coming from a template.</p>
</body>
</html>
views.py
from django.shortcuts import render
from django.http import HttpResponse


# Create your views here.
def home(request):
   return render(request,"home.html")
def second_page(request):
   return HttpResponse("second page")
Browser
 ↓
urls.py  → decides route
 ↓
views.py → calls render()
 ↓
templates/home.html
 ↓
Browser shows HTML
















